**REQUIREMENTS SPECIFICATION GENERATED BY THE LLM**
Functional Requirements
1)	FR-01. (System) The system shall display a welcome message and prompt the user to start the program by pressing SwiftBot button ‘A’.
Acceptance: When button A is pressed the CLI clears the welcome and proceeds to registration.

2)	FR-02. (System / User) The system shall prompt the user (via CLI) to enter their preferred player name using the keyboard. The user shall enter an alphanumeric name (no leading/trailing whitespace).
Acceptance: Name accepted only if it matches regex [A-Za-z0-9] {1,30}; otherwise show friendly error and re-prompt.


3)	FR-03. (System) The system shall assign a name to the SwiftBot automatically (random or configured). The user may optionally override this name via a CLI option before the first round.
Acceptance: SwiftBot name appears in move summaries and logs.

4)	FR-04. (System) The system shall roll a virtual 6-sided die for both players to determine who goes first. The player with the higher roll goes first and is assigned ‘O’ (noughts); the other is assigned ‘X’ (crosses). If a tie occurs, the system shall re-roll until tie resolved.
Acceptance: Die roll values displayed, first player and piece assignment displayed.

5)	FR-05. (User/System) On a human turn the user shall specify a move in the format [row, column] where row and column are integers 1-3. The system shall parse and validate the input.
Acceptance: Valid input accepted; invalid input triggers clear error message and re-prompt (no crash).

6)	FR-06. (System) The system shall prevent placement on an already occupied square. If user attempts that, the system shall inform the user and ask for a different move.
Acceptance: No move overwrites existing piece; log records the attempted invalid move.

7)	FR-07. (System) During the SwiftBot’s turn the system shall select the SwiftBot move (random by default) and announce the chosen square to the user in the CLI before the robot moves.
Acceptance: CLI shows e.g. [SwiftBot – X] will move to square [2,1] then SwiftBot moves.

8)	FR-08. (System → SwiftBot) After selecting its move, the System shall command the SwiftBot to physically travel to the target square, blink green 3 times, and return to its starting position on the board. The System is responsible for sending motion commands; SwiftBot executes them.
Acceptance: Motion command logged; LED blink sequence performed. (Motion accuracy is verified by calibration tests recorded in Implementation.)

9)	FR-09. (System) After every move (user or SwiftBot) the System shall update the CLI ASCII board and print a concise move summary: [Yasoda – O] moved to square [1,3].
Acceptance: ASCII board and a one-line summary displayed within 1–2 seconds of confirming the move.

10)	FR-10. (System) The system shall detect win or draw conditions after each move. For a winning line the System shall command the SwiftBot to trace the winning line and perform the appropriate LED effect: — User (O) win: blink green 3 times before and after tracing; — SwiftBot (X) win: blink red 3 times before and after tracing. For a draw, the SwiftBot shall spin once and blink blue 3 times.
Acceptance: Correct outcome detection and corresponding SwiftBot behaviour executed and logged.

11)	FR-11. (System) After each round the System shall append a round entry to a persistent log file containing round number, each move in order (player, piece, row, column), winner/draw, winning player name (or draw), and timestamp. The log file path shall be shown to the user on program termination.
Acceptance: Log file contains human-readable CSV or structured text entries.

12)	FR-12. (System) The System shall maintain a scoreboard across rounds (persisted during the program execution; persisted to disk on termination). A round win increments that player’s score by 1. The scoreboard shall be displayed after each round.
Acceptance: Scoreboard persists for the program session and is shown at end of each round.

13)	FR-13. (User/System) At the end of a round the user shall be prompted to continue (press SwiftBot ‘Y’) or quit (press SwiftBot ‘X’). If user quits the program, the system writes final logs, displays log path, and terminates cleanly.
Acceptance: On quit the program writes logs, shows file path and exits with message.

14)	FR-14. (System) The System shall enforce turn alternation — players must alternate moves and the System shall refuse out-of-turn moves.
Acceptance: Any out-of-turn input is rejected with a clear message and re-prompt.

15)	FR-15. (System) The System shall provide friendly, non-technical error messages for all input errors and will not crash on malformed input; it will re-prompt until valid input is received.
Acceptance: All invalid inputs produce single-line guidance (no stack traces) and allow retry.

16)	FR-16. (System) The System shall track the SwiftBot’s current location and orientation and use this to compute the motion commands necessary to reach each target square (uses calibrated seconds-per-25cm or equivalent parameter).
Acceptance: Motion planner parameters recorded in Implementation; motion commands reference current location/orientation. 

Non-functional requirements 

1)	NFR-01. (Interface) The program shall use a command-line interface (CLI) for all textual input/output. The CLI shall display the ASCII game board, move summaries, prompts and errors. 
2)	NFR-02. (Correctness) All game logic (move validation, win/draw detection, score updates) shall be fully testable; unit tests should exist for these modules. Measure: 100% deterministic unit tests for rules.
3)	NFR-03. (Input validation) The system shall validate all user inputs for format and range (e.g. [1,3] row/column) and reject anything outside 1..3 or non-numeric values. Error messages must be short and user-friendly.
4)	NFR-04. (Response time) The CLI shall update the board and display move summaries within 1–2 seconds of a confirmed move (excluding SwiftBot physical motion).
5)	NFR-05. (Logging) The system shall reliably append a round log entry for every round; the log shall survive program crashes where possible (flush to disk after each round).
6)	NFR-06. (Modularity & Readability) The codebase shall be modular (separate modules: input handling, game logic, motion command interface, logging) and include inline comments describing each public function’s purpose.  
7)	NFR-07. (Safety & Calibration) The SwiftBot movement must be calibrated so that travel distances per square are accurate (± acceptable tolerance). The environment must be well lit to observe LEDs/shapes. Measure: calibration routine verifies that motion for 25 cm is within ±10% before game start. 
8)	NFR-08. (Robustness) The system shall handle unexpected exceptions gracefully (log the exception, display a friendly message, and return to a safe state rather than crash).
9)	NFR-09. (Usability) Error messages shall be concise and actionable; the CLI should show brief instructions for first-time users. 
10)	NFR-10. (Testability) The game logic should be independent of the SwiftBot hardware interface so it can be fully tested in a hardware-free mode (mock/swapped interface). Acceptance: tests run in CI without robot attached.
Additional functionalities 
1)	AF-01. (Undo — limited) (User/System) Provide an Undo feature: user may undo their last move up to two times per game. When undo is invoked via a CLI command (e.g. undo), the System reverts the last move (both board state and logged move), updates the scoreboard/state accordingly, and repositions SwiftBot to its pre-move location (motion command).

2)	AF-02. (Move Timer — configurable) (User/System) Optional per-game timer: the user can enable a turn timer (configurable between 5–10 seconds) before the first round. If enabled, the System starts a timer when prompting for the user’s move; if the user does not submit a valid move before timeout, the turn is forfeited and control passes to the SwiftBot.

3)	AF-03. (Adaptive SwiftBot difficulty & movement style) (System) Provide two SwiftBot move strategies selectable at game start: Random (default) and Strategic (minimax or heuristic). When Strategic is selected, the System computes the best board move and additionally causes SwiftBot to use a different LED pattern and slightly faster movement on decisive moves (visual feedback).
Improvements made to the initial SRS 
One of the improvements made to generated SRS was to keep the functional, non-functional requirements and additional functionalities atomic, clear and precise. The original SRS generated by the LLM covers all the functional, non-functional requirements and additional functionalities but each requirement is too complex and detailed, which would affect how the requirements are translated to the flowchart and pseudocode later. Keeping it atomic and simpler would make implementation a lot easier to follow and saves time. 
Additionally, I had double-checked the generated srs to ensure that all requirements were met and ensured that the requirements followed a logical sequential order, which ensured that it makes it easier to follow step by step before planning the flowchart and pseudocode to reduce the chance making mistakes beforehand. 
